Question 1: In your own words, explain Web Engineering.
Ans: Web Engineering is the systematic application of software engineering principles to the design, development, deployment, and maintenance of web applications.
It treats web systems as full-scale software products rather than simple web pages. Web Engineering focuses on understanding user requirements, designing efficient architectures, developing reliable code, testing for quality, and maintaining applications over time. It also emphasizes usability, accessibility, security, scalability, and performance, since web applications are highly interactive and used by large numbers of users.
In short, Web Engineering ensures that web applications are built in a structured, reliable, and professional manner, making them easy to use, secure, and maintainable in a rapidly changing web environment
The Web Engineering Process (Lifecycle) describes the structured stages followed to develop and maintain a web application efficiently. It typically includes the following phases:
1.	Requirements Analysis
Identifies user needs, system functions, and non-functional requirements such as performance, security, and usability.
2.	Design
Defines the system architecture, database structure, navigation flow, user interface, and content layout.
3.	Development (Implementation)
Involves coding the front end and back end, integrating databases, APIs, and other services.
4.	Testing
Ensures the application works correctly through functional, usability, performance, security, and compatibility testing.
5.	Deployment
Releases the web application to a live environment with proper server configuration and security settings.
6.	Maintenance and Evolution
Includes fixing bugs, updating content, improving performance, adding new features, and handling security updates.

Question 2: Explore and list core technologies used in Web Engineering, including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and PHP, and explain the role of each.
Ans: 
1. HTML (HyperText Markup Language)
HTML is the standard markup language used to create and structure web pages. It defines the content and structure of a website by using tags and elements. HTML tells the browser what content to display, such as text, images, links, and forms.
Role in Web Engineering:
•	Creates the basic structure of web pages
•	Defines headings, paragraphs, tables, forms, and multimedia
•	Uses semantic elements to improve accessibility and SEO
Example:
A webpage’s layout with a header, navigation bar, main content, and footer is created using HTML.
2. CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)
CSS is used to control the visual appearance of a web page. It works alongside HTML by applying styles such as colors, fonts, spacing, and layouts. CSS ensures that websites look attractive and consistent across different devices.
Role in Web Engineering:
•	Styles text, images, and backgrounds
•	Controls layout using Flexbox and Grid
•	Makes websites responsive for mobile, tablet, and desktop screens
•	Adds animations and visual effects
Example:
Using CSS to change font colors, align elements, and design a responsive layout.

3. JavaScript
JavaScript is a scripting language that enables interactivity and dynamic behavior on web pages. It runs in the user’s browser and allows websites to respond to user actions without reloading the page.
Role in Web Engineering:
•	Handles user events like clicks and keystrokes
•	Validates forms on the client side
•	Updates content dynamically (e.g., live search results)
•	Communicates with servers using AJAX
Example:
Showing an alert message when a button is clicked or validating a form before submission.
4. PHP (Hypertext Preprocessor)
PHP is a server-side scripting language used to build dynamic websites. It runs on the server and processes data before sending the final HTML output to the browser.
Role in Web Engineering:
•	Processes form submissions
•	Connects to and manages databases
•	Handles user authentication and sessions
•	Generates dynamic web content
Example:
Processing a login form and retrieving user data from a database.
Summary Table
Technology	Main Purpose	Runs On
HTML	Structure and content	Browser
CSS	Styling and layout	Browser
JavaScript	Interactivity and logic	Browser
PHP	Server-side processing	Server

Question 3: Identify front-end and back-end technologies used in web development and give examples of each.
Ans: Web development is commonly divided into front-end (client-side) and back-end (server-side) technologies. Here’s a clear breakdown with examples:
1.	Front-End Technologies (Client-Side)
These are responsible for what users see and interact with in their browsers.
Core Technologies
•	HTML (HyperText Markup Language)
Structures web content (headings, paragraphs, forms, images).
•	CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)
Styles and layouts the website (colors, fonts, responsive design).
